# AI Sliding Puzzle Lab – Design Document

## 1. Overview

AI Sliding Puzzle Lab is an Android application implementing the classic **3×3 Sliding Puzzle (8-Puzzle)** using **Artificial Intelligence search algorithms**. The application demonstrates how the **A* search algorithm** can optimally solve combinatorial problems while exposing algorithmic metrics to the user in real time.

The app allows players to interact with the puzzle while visualizing the internal state of the solver.

---

## 2. Architecture

The application follows the **MVVM (Model–View–ViewModel)** architecture.

Flow:

UI (Jetpack Compose Screens)
      ↓
ViewModel (State + Game Logic)
      ↓
AI Solver Logic (A* Algorithm)

This separation ensures:

• Clear state management  
• Easy UI updates using reactive flows  
• Decoupling of algorithmic logic from UI

---

## 3. UI Layer

Location:
screens/sliding_puzzle/

Components:

PuzzleScreen.kt  
PuzzleBoard.kt  
Tile.kt

Responsibilities:

PuzzleScreen
• Main container screen
• Displays metrics
• Contains control buttons
• Hosts puzzle board

PuzzleBoard
• Renders the 3×3 grid
• Handles swipe gestures
• Handles tile taps

Tile
• Displays tile number
• Handles tile styling
• Supports highlight state for hints

UI built using **Jetpack Compose**.

---

## 4. ViewModel Layer

File:
PuzzleViewModel.kt

Responsibilities:

• Manage board state  
• Track player moves  
• Calculate efficiency score  
• Request solver computation  
• Maintain hint and autosolve state

State is managed using:

StateFlow

Key state variables:

board  
currentMoves  
optimalMoves  
searchDepth  
heuristic  
hintTile  
isSolved  

---

## 5. Logic Layer

Location:
logic/sliding_puzzle/

Core components:

AStarSolver.kt  
PuzzleState.kt  
ManhattanHeuristic.kt  
PuzzleGenerator.kt  
SolveResult.kt

Responsibilities:

AStarSolver
• Executes the A* search algorithm

PuzzleState
• Represents nodes in the search tree

ManhattanHeuristic
• Calculates heuristic cost

PuzzleGenerator
• Generates solvable puzzle boards

SolveResult
• Stores solver results

---

## 6. A* Search Algorithm

The puzzle is solved using the **A* search algorithm**.

Evaluation function:

f(n) = g(n) + h(n)

Where:

g(n) = cost from start state  
h(n) = heuristic estimate to goal  

The solver prioritizes states with the smallest f(n).

---

## 7. Manhattan Distance Heuristic

The heuristic used is **Manhattan Distance**.

For each tile:

distance = |x1 - x2| + |y1 - y2|

The heuristic value is the sum of distances for all tiles from their goal positions.

This heuristic is **admissible**, meaning it never overestimates the cost to reach the goal.

---

## 8. Puzzle Representation

The puzzle board is stored as:

IntArray(9)

Example board state:

[1,2,3,
 4,5,6,
 7,0,8]

Where:

0 represents the empty tile.

---

## 9. Difficulty Generation

Puzzle difficulty is controlled through **scramble depth**.

Easy: 10–14 moves  
Medium: 16–22 moves  
Hard: 24–30 moves  
Expert: 30–35 moves

The board is generated by applying random valid moves from the solved state.

---

## 10. Performance Considerations

• Solver runs on background thread using:

Dispatchers.Default

• UI state updates are reactive using:

StateFlow

• Puzzle generation avoids unsolvable states.

Worst-case search complexity for the 8-puzzle is approximately:

181,440 reachable states.

Maximum optimal solution length:

31 moves.

---

## 11. UI Design Principles

• Minimalist interface  
• Large square tiles for touch accuracy  
• Centralized puzzle layout  
• Real-time algorithm metrics display  

---

## 12. Future Enhancements

Possible improvements include:

• 4×4 (15-puzzle) support  
• Advanced heuristics (Linear Conflict)  
• IDA* search optimization  
• Timer-based challenges  
• Leaderboards  
• Multiplayer puzzle solving